                            <div id="section1">
                                <h4>
                                    <strong>What are alternative assets and what is driving their popularity right now?</strong>
                                </h4>
                            </div>
                            <p>
                                <p>
                                    Alternative assets refer to assets that don’t fall into the traditional investment categories like listed shares, bonds and
                                    cash. Alternative assets include things like venture capital, private equity and property.
                                    The popularity of alternative assets has been growing exponentially over the last decade
                                    and, according to PwC, is forecast to boom over the next few years growing from AuM of
                                    US$2.9 trillion in 2017 to $US 6.9 trillion by 2025, which is a massive CAGR of 11.7%.

                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    The reasons for the rise in popularity of alternative assets is twofold:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    1. &nbsp;&nbsp;
                                    <strong>High Growth:</strong> Alternative assets offer the opportunity for significantly higher
                                    returns than listed stocks, bonds or cash. And in this low return and low growth environment,
                                    everybody is looking for upside that actually moves the needle - alternative assets can
                                    do that, defensive assets generally do not. Of course, as with any other investment strategy,
                                    risk needs to be taken into consideration when investing in alternative assets.
                                    <br/><br/> 2. &nbsp;&nbsp;
                                    <strong>Direct Access:</strong> Venture Capital and Equity Crowdfunding enable investors to connect
                                    more directly with purpose-driven projects that make a positive contribution to the planet
                                    in a way that traditional assets cannot. Investors are absolutely looking for growth,
                                    but they also want to know their investment dollars are contributing to a better world.
                                </p>

                                <div id="section2">
                                    <h4>
                                        <strong>
                                            What do investors need to consider when weighing up the risk versus the return?<br/>
                                        </strong>
                                    </h4>
                                </div>
                                <p>
                                    When a new business idea is conceived, it starts from a plan on a piece of paper and a series of assumptions. For example:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    “What if there was a platform that allowed ordinary people to rent out rooms in their houses to travellers on a short-term
                                    basis in the same way that hotels rent out rooms.”
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    There are 3 key assumptions being made in that idea:

                                    <p>
                                        1. &nbsp;&nbsp; That homeowners would want and be prepared to rent out a room in their house to a stranger on a short-term
                                        basis  <br/>
                                    
                                        2. &nbsp;&nbsp; That travellers would want to rent a room in someone else's house  <br/>
                                    
                                        3. &nbsp;&nbsp; That the team behind the idea could build a platform that connected those people effectively
                                    </p>

                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    All of those things were unknown risks when the idea of
                                    <strong>Airbnb</strong> was first conceived in 2009. There were many high profile investors who
                                    rejected the idea. But those who invested at the beginning ($20k) at a valuation of $2.5M
                                    did very well, with the company listing on the NASDAQ last year at a valuation of over
                                    $100 billion. And to think that almost all unicorns like Airbnb are born in rejection!
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    As a startup goes through a series of growth phases, it gradually de-risks itself by proving out the assumptions it started
                                    with or pivoting and changing course, just like Airbnb did. So, yes, risk needs to be
                                    considered, but nothing truly great has ever been achieved without a group of people
                                    coming together and taking a little risk. That’s the foundation of equity crowdfunding,
                                    enabling founders and investors to be bold and shape the future.
                                </p>
                                <div id="section3">
                                    <h4>
                                        <strong>
                                            How has COVID affected the Australian startup scene? <br/>
                                        </strong>
                                    </h4>
                                </div>
                                <p>
                                    Before the GFC, the Australian startup sector and the venture capital industry was almost non-existent. Last year, there
                                    were 227 Australian venture capital investment deals done with a reported $1.6 billion
                                    invested. In retail equity crowdfunding, the number was around $47 million.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Today the Australian startup ecosystem is one of the fastest-growing globally, and what has helped that growth is the success
                                    of so many awesome Australian startups that have gone on to become massive global businesses,
                                    including a large number that have reached unicorn status - or valuations of over $1
                                    billion - such as
                                    <strong> Go1, Canva, AfterPay, Judo Capital, Airwallex</strong> and
                                    <strong>Nearmap.</strong>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Right now, we are seeing an even greater number of really interesting Australian startups that have the potential to be just
                                    as big. Accounting for the fact that in 2020 the alternative finance market was valued
                                    at over $1 billion (double that of the value in 2016), we can foresee this sector playing
                                    a key role in supporting more and more early-stage startups in their journey towards
                                    joining the unicorn club.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    At VentureCrowd, we are feeling bullish and we believe this will be the biggest year ever for the Australian startup sector.
                                </p>
                                <div id="section4">
                                    <h4>
                                        <strong>
                                            What are the things investors should consider when investing in startups and how can investors find out more? <br/>
                                        </strong>
                                    </h4>
                                </div>
                                <p>
                                    There are a number of things to think about when considering whether to invest in a startup. At VentureCrowd, our venture
                                    capital team focus on the following:
                                </p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <strong>Always back the jockey, not the horse: </strong> The team needs to be rock solid.
                                        The world’s best idea in the hands of a dysfunctional team is an idea destined to
                                        fail.
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <strong>The problem:</strong> The business needs to be solving a large enough problem for
                                        a large enough group of people so that its total addressable market is significant
                                        and not just a small niche. Ideally, it has to have global potential.
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <strong>The exit:</strong> The business must have a clearly defined exit strategy. This is
                                        when investors realise a return from their investment, so there needs to be a reasonable
                                        line of sight to a merger, trade sale, or a listing that makes sense for that business.
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <strong> Purpose:</strong> Impact investing is here to stay and brands that will succeed in
                                        the future are those that align with their customers through their purpose. At VentureCrowd,
                                        we only invest in businesses that are purpose-driven. That means they must address
                                        one or more of the UN sustainable development goals. That’s because we know our investors
                                        want their investments to have high-growth potential but also to have a positive
                                        impact on the planet.
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                                    <p>
                                        So if you want exposure to these types of startup opportunities, you can head to the VentureCrowd website for more information.
